04163nam a22006615i 9786155053122DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222020hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2020940851  a9786155053122  a(DE-B1597)633481  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aMLCM 2022/40253 (B) 4aBF1584.U38bD97 2020 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a133.4/3094772231 aDysa, Kateryna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUkrainian Witchcraft Trials :bVolhynia, Podolia, and Ruthenia, 17th–18th Centuries /cKateryna Dysa. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Constructing the Ukrainian Witchcraft Trial -- tChapter 2 Ukrainian Orthodox Demonology: The Learned Elite and Perceptions of the Devil and Witches -- tChapter 3 Beyond the Trials, or the Anatomy of Witchcraft Accusations -- tChapter 4 A Case of Witchcraft and Infanticide in Szczurowczyky -- tFurther Romanticization, Forgetting, and Resurrection of Ukrainian Witches: An Afterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUkrainian Witchcraft Trials is an analysis of early modern witchcraft trials and legal procedures in Ukrainian lands, along with an examination of quantitative data drawn from the different trials. Kateryna Dysa first describes the ideological background of the tribunals based on works written by priests and theologians that reflect attitudes towards the devil and witches. The main focus of her work, however, is the process leading to witchcraft accusations. From the stories of participants of the trials she shows what led people to enunciate first suspicions then accusations of witchcraft. Finally, she presents a microhistory from one Volhynian village, comparing attitudes towards two "female crimes" in the Ukrainian courts. The study is based on archival research together with previously published witch trials transcripts. Dysa approaches the trials as indications of belief and practice, attempting to understand the actors involved rather than dismiss or condemn them. She takes care to situate Ukrainian witchcraft and its accompanying trials in a broader European context, with comparisons to some African cases as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aTrials (Witchcraft)zUkrainexHistoryy17th century. 0aTrials (Witchcraft)zUkrainexHistoryy18th century. 0aWitchcraftzUkrainexHistoryy17th century. 0aWitchcraftzUkrainexHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aDemonology, Early modern Europe, Ethnography, Folklore, Ukraine, Witchcraft.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2020z978311078050540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155053122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155053122/original  a978-3-11-078050-5  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK